font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">1. Independent expert =
testing</span></b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">You indicated that Tower/you will =
not pay for any expert testing as part of my preparation of the claim, =
as you said that is what you are already doing. However, I am struggling =
to understand this position. =46rom my perspective, you are preparing =
the claim from Tower=E2=80=99s side, and I have not been invited to or =
involved in any of the NZRSC<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: =
rgb(0, 112, 192);">[can you please clarify what NZRSC stands for? =E2=80=93=
 I am sorry, I am not familiar with this acronym]<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span>assessments or =
discussions. This does not feel independent or transparent from my =
side.<span class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span =
style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">Attached are the material damage =
Report &amp; Scope of repair works as provided by our technical Building =
consultant. These are provided to you for your reference and review. I =
received these from ASURNZ o Friday 5<sup>th</sup><span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>September. =
&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">Given the seriousness of the fire, =
and the chemical involvement (including spa chemicals with corrosive =
chlorides and bromides), I am concerned that critical risks may be =
under-assessed. Could you please clarify why Tower would not support me =
in engaging independent engineers, hygienists, or other specialists to =
provide an impartial view?<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: =
rgb(0, 112, 192);">We can provide independent swab-testing by a forensic =
scientist, which tests for chemical contamination which has occurred =
from the fire. I would need to meet with you to have you provide context =
and detail on exactly what chemicals were present and where they were =
located within the property. I am happy to progress this process further =
with you as soon as possible =E2=80=93 but I will need to establish more =
context and detail as to what this potential contamination may be, =
before we undertake any testing. We can also share the methodology of =
the forensic testing with you before we undertake the testing. =
&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: =
9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">Further, I request that I =
be&nbsp;included in all communications with any assessors&nbsp;and 3rd =
parties=E2=80=94 including texts, emails, calls, and meetings =E2=80=94 =
and that these be scheduled so I have the opportunity to participate. =
This is essential for transparency and to ensure I am properly informed =
about the basis of decisions being made.<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: =
rgb(0, 112, 192);">I can accommodate this as much as is practically =
possible. I have kept you fully informed of every step and process that =
I have undertaken to date when progressing your claim. I understand that =
you have made a privacy request to our claims department =E2=80=93 which =
will provide you with access to all communications regarding your claim. =
I will forward this request that you have made to a<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><u>Senior Claims =
Manager</u><span class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=E2=80=93 =
so that they can respond to your request in a more comprehensive =
response. This is a Claims Management request =E2=80=93 whereas my focus =
is on the structural repairs required for your claim. Please allow to =
forward and escalate this request for you. =
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">2. =
Structural elements =E2=80=93 linings and framing</span></b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">You mentioned that, in addition to =
demolishing and rebuilding the closed deck, your intention is to replace =
only a couple of structural beams and to rely on methods such as dry-ice =
blasting and thermal fogging for the bricks. =46rom a technical =
perspective, this seems inadequate =
because:<o:p></o:p></span></p><div><ol start=3D"1" type=3D"1" =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in; margin-top: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">Smoke odour and residue remain even on the first floor =E2=80=
=94 the least affected part of the house =E2=80=94 three months after =
the fire, suggesting deep penetration.<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">The fire involved =
spa chemicals, creating corrosive residues (chlorides, bromides) likely =
absorbed into linings, timber framing, and fixings.<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: =
rgb(0, 112, 192);">I have responded to this as above.</span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">Superficial cleaning, fogging, or painting over residues =
cannot ensure long-term safety or durability.<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Bricks and mortar =
are porous: once penetrated by smoke and chemical residues, they can =
continue to off-gas and deteriorate over time, undermining both =
habitability and structural performance.<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">&nbsp;<span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">Similarly, timber framing, structural timbers, and =
plasterboard linings are fibrous and absorbent. Once smoke and chemical =
residues penetrate, they may release odours, compromise air quality, =
accelerate corrosion of embedded fixings, and create conditions for =
hidden mould or decay. These risks cannot be fully eliminated by surface =
cleaning<span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Your approach appears to focus only on visible =
damage (e.g. darkened beams), while overlooking non-visible but equally =
serious fire, smoke, and water impacts. This is not appropriate, creates =
significant long-term risks, and is not aligned with Tower=E2=80=99s =
obligation to reinstate the house to an =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
standard.<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ol></div><div><div><div style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">On that basis, =
could you clarify how retaining contaminated bricks, timbers, and =
linings meets Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstate the property to a =
=E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard? What testing and certification is =
planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =
=E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div></div><div><div><div style=3D"margin:=
 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">&nbsp;<span =
style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div></div><div><div><div style=3D"margin:=
 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><b>3. Roof =
assessment</b><span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div></div><p><span style=3D"font-size: =
9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">You indicated that the roof =
requires no work. I find this difficult to reconcile with the =
evidence<span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">: [ with respect I said =
that there was no structural fire damage in the roof space. It could be =
accepted that there is a faint smoke odour in the roof space from any =
smoke which may have passed through this space. We have allowed for =
replacement of 95 sqm of ceiling insulation to eliminate the possibility =
of any smoke odours remaining.</span><span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><=
ol start=3D"1" type=3D"1" style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in; margin-top: =
0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; =
font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Large volumes of black smoke were seen =
coming out from all sides of the roof during the fire.<span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">A gutter was significantly heat-damaged.<span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif; =
color: rgb(0, 112, 192);"><span style=3D"color: windowtext;">Local =
reporting even suggested the fire appeared to be in the roof. I have =
been in the roof space.<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span>There is no =
structural fire damage in the roof space.<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">If external heat was sufficient to =
damage guttering, then internal elements such as roof cavity insulation, =
underlay, battens, fixings, and trusses may also have been affected. =
Could you please clarify what inspection methods were used to conclude =
the roof was undamaged? Were cavity inspections, intrusive checks, or =
residue/chemical tests undertaken? What testing and certification is =
planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =
=E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">4. =
Services =E2=80=93 gas, electricity, and water</span></b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">I understand that you are going to =
test the gas unit and propose a plan to bring it up to new standard, =
which I appreciate. However, could you also please clarify what is =
planned for the &nbsp;electricty system, which suffered significant and =
widespread damage and the water distribution =
system<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">At present I am unclear how these =
critical services will be properly tested and reinstated. What testing =
and certification is planned to ensure these critical services are =
restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
condition?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">5. Timing and completeness of =
assessments</span></b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: =
Helvetica, sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size:=
 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">I am also confused and =
&nbsp;concerned that a repair plan is already being discussed before =
full assessments have been completed and before I have seen the NZRSC or =
other formal reports.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: =
9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">Could you clarify why Tower is =
progressing toward a repair plan at this stage rather than awaiting =
intrusive testing, particularly given the involvement of corrosive =
chemicals and deep smoke penetration? What testing and certification is =
planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =
=E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And what would be the sequencing of =
those to inform a realistic plan?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">In =
addition, is it not too risky to wait until after restructuring works to =
determine whether the house is safe and meets code requirements? That =
approach could prolong reinstatement unnecessarily, leaving me at =
greater disadvantage with accommodation costs and delays that are =
outside my control.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">6. Testing =
and reporting</span></b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: =
Helvetica, sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size:=
 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">Could you please =
confirm:<o:p></o:p></span></p><ol start=3D"1" type=3D"1" =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in; margin-top: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">What tests or assessments have actually been completed so =
far?<span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Why, given the involvement of spa chemicals, no =
intrusive testing has been arranged?<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">When the NZRSC =
report and other reports will be made available to me?<span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">What testing and certification is planned to ensure my =
house restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And =
could you please provide sequencing and timings.<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p><b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">7. Accommodation support -<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span></b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif; color: =
rgb(0, 112, 192);">Claims Manager will answer these questions for =
you.<span class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><p><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">A number =
of critical assessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 including tests for =
chemical penetration, the roof structure and cavity, and essential =
services such as electricity and water. Until these are properly =
completed and confirmed, the house is =
uninhabitable.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">At present, my rental accommodation =
is being funded under the contents policy ($30,000 limit). However, with =
reinstatement not yet underway and key assessments still pending, it is =
clear this allowance will be insufficient. These delays are entirely =
outside my control.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: =
9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">The Fair Insurance Code =
requires insurers to act fairly and not disadvantage customers through =
delay. The principle of insurance is to restore the insured to the =
pre-loss position. To avoid being placed at a further disadvantage, I =
would like to explore the following options:<o:p></o:p></span></p><ol =
start=3D"1" type=3D"1" style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in; margin-top: =
0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; =
font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Option A: Tower agrees I may take the =
lead in arranging necessary assessments and reinstatement works, =
provided all works are to =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard, meet =
current Building Code requirements, and remain within the insured sum. =
Tower would reimburse incurred costs within 15 days of invoice on a =
monthly basis, ensuring timely progress without administrative =
delay.<span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Option B: Alternatively, Tower confirms that it will =
continue to cover my accommodation costs until the house is fully =
restored and habitable, given that ongoing delays are not of my =
making.<span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">Could you please confirm which of =
these approaches Tower is prepared to adopt, so that I am not unfairly =
disadvantaged by circumstances outside my =
control?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">8. Privacy Act material =E2=80=93<spa=
n class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span></b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif; color: =
rgb(0, 112, 192);">Claims Manager will answer these questions for =
you.<span class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">You previously referred me to =
information provided under the Privacy Act, which I could not find. I =
found those two email but the links I received do not open or function. =
Could you please resend this information, ensuring that the links are =
accessible, or alternatively provide the documents as direct PDF/email =
attachments?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><b><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">Summary point</span></b><span =
style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: Helvetica, =
sans-serif;"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif;">At present, I remain unclear how =
Tower=E2=80=99s proposed approach =E2=80=94 which appears to favor =
superficial cleaning and limited replacement =E2=80=94 can reasonably =
restore my property to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
standard, particularly given the deep smoke and chemical penetration of =
bricks, timbers, and linings, the unresolved questions regarding the =
roof structure and cavity, and the uncertainty around full reinstatement =
of essential services such as electricity, water, and =
gas.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; font-family: =
Helvetica, sans-serif;">I would greatly appreciate your clarification on =
each of these points so that I can properly understand how my home will =
be restored to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
standard,<o:p></o:p></span></p><p><span style=3D"font-size: 9pt; =
